"script": "Beneath every forest, the trees are secretly talking to each other. Their roots are wrapped in a vast web of fungus, threads so fine they stretch for miles underground. And the trees use this network like a hidden internet, trading sugar, water, and even warning signals. You see, when one tree is attacked by insects, it sends a chemical alarm through the fungus to its neighbors. This means the others can start pumping out defenses before the bugs ever arrive. Scientists call it the wood wide web, an entire forest quietly looking out for itself.",
